The primary reason for bull barrels is accuracy. The larger diameter results in more stiffness and repeatability shot to shot.

The next advantage is recoil management. With this larger barrel diameter comes additional weight. Usually this is a liability, but since bull barreled ARs are usually shot from a bipod or sandbags the additional weight of the barrel helps keep the rifle in position. A 12-14 pound AR in .223 is a joy to shoot. Often bullet impact can be observed because recoil is so minimal.

The final advantage in my opinion is velocity. Since weight conservation is already out the window, many bull barrel makers take advantage of this and make the barrel longer. A 24" or even the 26" WOA barrel offer additional velocity that makes these tack drivers flat shooters as well.

Call or text REDACTED

title: For Sale:  Hornady 366 Progressive Shot Shell Loader
postcontent:
If you're an avid trap, skeet, sporting clays shooter or devoted bird hunter, what could be better than a day in the field? Certainly not a day at your reloading table. Which is why Hornady created the 366 Auto, a machine that cranks out low-cost reloads in a hurry, so you can spend more time shooting. It's easy. All you do is set in an empty case and wad, and then pull the operating lever. Everything else is done for you-automatically. Every stroke turns out a precisely crimped shell, fully resized to factory dimensions.

The 366 Auto features full-length resizing, automatic primer feed, swing-out wad guide, three-stage Taper-Loc crimping, automatic advance to the next station, automatic ejection and one primer tube filler. Additional die sets are available in 12, 20, and 28 gauge.

This Hornady 366 reloading press is sized for 12 Ga.

I have upgraded this machine with a spring loaded Primer Seater, Extended Primer Tube.

Includes a bunch of Wads, ~2lbs of WST Powder, 2 bags of Shot

Asking $400 FTF Preferred, Shipping on your dime.

title: For Sale:  16" Mid Length AR15 brand new
postcontent:
I just built this rifle, it has never been fired since the build. I have two 16" mid length AR15s and want to sell one to start funding another car project.

Its a Delton 16" 1-7" twist mid length chrome lined medium contour upper with a high pressure tested and magnetic particle inspected bolt and chrome lined carrier. These uppers come test fired from Delton since the bolts are high pressure tested and that is the only time this rifle has been fired. I cleaned the bolt and the rest of the upper when UPS brought it to me and lubed it up. Has A2 flash hider and hand guards and "F" marked front sight base with a carry handle. It will need sighted in as I have not fired it.

The lower is an RGuns lower that I bought stripped along with a lower parts kit. I assembled the lower with an A2 milspec fixed stock and did a little work on cleaning up the trigger machining marks so it isnt gritty. Trigger feels nice and breaks clean.

It doesn't have all the bells and whistles of a tactical mall ninja AR15, but it is a nice basic chrome lined rifle that will teach you to shoot with iron sights instead of a cheap red dot scope.

The price is pretty firm but cash is king. AR15 stuff is still on backorder for a while and hard to get a hold of. I do not want trades unless you have liquid cooled volkswagen parts. Particularly a 4 cylinder 02A transmission and ABA motor stuff.
